║                                                        Storage Management                                                       ║
╚═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

   Display Block Devices
   ─────────────────────
      1. Open a terminal window
      2. Login as the superuser (root on CentOS/RHEL)
      3. To display the layout of all the block devices, execute the following command

            lsblk --all


   System Storage Manager
   ──────────────────────
      1. Open a terminal window
      2. Login as the superuser (root on CentOS/RHEL)
      3. If the tool is not installed, execute the following command:

            yum --noplugins --enablerepo "*" --disablerepo "*media*" install system-storage-manager

      4. To manage the storage on the system, execute the following command:

            ssm list

      5. To add a new volume to an existing pool, execute the following command:

            ssm create -s <size> -n <name> --fstype <type> -p <pool> <device> <mount-point>
            (example command: ssm create -s 20G -n tftpboot --fstype xfs -p VG2 /dev/sda6 /tftpboot)

      6. To resize an existing volume, execute the following command:

            ssm resize -s<size> <volume>
            (example command: ssm resize -s+20G /dev/VG2/tftpboot)


   Gnome Partition Editor
   ──────────────────────
      1. Open a terminal window
      2. Login as the superuser (root on CentOS/RHEL)
      3. To manage the storage partitions on the system, execute the following command

            gparted



